04768nam a22006375i 9780813560120DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19921992nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135601207 a10.36019/97808135601202doi  a(DE-B1597)530118  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPOL0000002bisacsh1 aHirsch, Arnold, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUrban Policy In 20th Century /cRaymond A Mohl, Arnold Hirsch. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[1992] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource (250 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tContributors -- t1 Shifting Patterns of American Urban Policy since 1900 -- t2 Surviving Poverty in Early Twentieth-Century New York City -- t3 With or Without Jim Crow: Black Residential Segregation in the United States -- t4 Race and Space in the Modern City: Interstate-95 and the Black Community in Miami -- t5 Black Political Power and Public Policy in the Urban South -- t6 Through Flight to Tokyo: Sunbelt Cities and the New World Economy, 1960-1990 -- t7 Eco-Urbanism and Past Choices for Urban Living -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe recent riots in Los Angeles brought the urban crisis back to the center of public policy debates in Washington, D.C., and in urban areas throughout the United States. The contributors to this volume examine the major policy issues--race, housing, transportation, poverty, the changing environment, the effects of the global economy--confronting contemporary American cities. Raymond A. Mohl begins with an extended discussion of the origins, evolution, and current state of Federal involvement in urban centers. Michael B. Katz follows with an insightful look at poverty in turn-of-the-century New York and the attempts to ameliorate the desperate plight of the poor during this period of rapid economic growth. Arnold R. Hirsch, Mohl, and David R. Goldfield then pursue different facets of the racial dilemma confronting American cities. Hirsch discusses historical dimensions of residential segregation and public policy, while Mohl uses Overtown, Miami, as a case study of the social impact of the construction of interstate highways in urban communities. David Goldfield explores the political ramifications and incongruities of contemporary urban race relations. Finally, Carl Abbott and Sam Bass Warner, Jr., examine the impact of global economic developments and the environmental implications of past policy choices. Collectively, the authors show us where we have been, some of the needs that must be addressed, and the urban policy alternatives we face.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAbbott, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBass Warner, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldfield, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirsch, Arnold R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatz, Michael B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMohl, Raymond A, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMohl, Raymond A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311066333440uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356012040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813560120423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813560120/original  a978-3-11-066333-4  Rutgers University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BAC